### 5. Use Indexed Access Types for Safe Property Access

TypeScript’s Indexed Access Types provide a powerful way to work with complex object structures. This feature ensures type safety when accessing nested properties, helping you avoid common errors and write more reliable code.

interface Order {

 id: string;

 customer: {

 name: string;

 email: string;

 };

 items: {

 product: Product;

 quantity: number;

 }[];

}

type CustomerEmail = Order['customer']['email']; // Type is string [...] ## Conclusion

In this blog, we explored powerful TypeScript features that enhance development while promoting best practices and clean code. Strong typing serves as the foundation for clear, self-documenting code, catching errors early in the process. A modular code structure improves maintainability and scalability, while generics foster flexibility and reusability, adhering to the DRY principle.

Utility types like `Partial`, `Pick`, `Readonly`, and `Omit` provide clean solutions for common type transformations, enhancing code clarity. Conditional and mapped types offer elegant ways to manage complex type relationships, leading to more expressive and maintainable code.
